 Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Leuchars","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from Leuchars (Fife)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewars","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leuchars  ."]},{"name":"Lewers","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewer  .","Scottish: variant of <b>Leuchars</b>, a habitational name from Leuchars in Fife. The placename derives from Gaelic <i>luachar</i> ‘reed, rush’ + the English plural <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ness","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of unknown origin; borne by a character in <i>Táin Bó Cuailgne</i> (the Cattle Raid of Cooley), the mother of Conchobhar."],"variants":[{"name":"Neassa","meanings":["Traditional name of unknown origin; borne by a character in <i>Táin Bó Cuailgne</i> (the Cattle Raid of Cooley), the mother of Conchobhar."]},{"name":"Neasa","meanings":["Traditional name of unknown origin; borne by a character in <i>Táin Bó Cuailgne</i> (the Cattle Raid of Cooley), the mother of Conchobhar."]},{"name":"Vanessa","meanings":["Name invented by  Jonathan Swift  (  1667–1745 ) for his friend  Esther Vanhomrigh . It seems to have been derived from the first syllable of her (Dutch) surname, with the addition of the suffix <i>-essa</i> (perhaps influenced by the first syllable of her given name). The name became fairly popular in the 20th century, being borne for example by the actress 